---
import SimpleContentLayout from '@layouts/SimpleContentLayout.astro';

const content = {
  title: 'About Aletheia',
  description: 'What Aletheia is, why the public archive stays open, and how it is built and maintained.',
};
---

<SimpleContentLayout content={content}>
  <h2>What Is Aletheia?</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Aletheia</strong> is an original fantasy world developed for tabletop role-playing games. This site serves
    as an open fantasy worldbuilding and campaign archive: the canonical reference for the setting's history,
    cultures, locations, assumptions, and internal logic.
  </p>

  <p>
    The material here has grown out of decades of play and world-building. It is intended to support long-term
    campaigns and thoughtful exploration of the setting, rather than provide a fixed narrative or single "official"
    story.
  </p>

  <p>
    The public direction of the project is archive-first rather than business-first. The goal is to make the world
    readable, useful, and trustworthy while leaving room for the campaign platform to mature over time.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Open Source and Service Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>World of Aletheia</strong> is maintained as an open-source and open-access project, dedicated to ensuring
    its public code and archive remain open source. That includes Canon, Using Aletheia, Reference, and the
    public-facing archive material that ties them together.
  </p>

  <p>
    If optional paid work appears in the future, it is more likely to be campaign-specific and additive: private
    campaign hosting, seamless connectivity to the Canon and Reference layers, storage, availability,
    authentication/access control, backups, and operational support for individual groups. Those services would add to
    the project rather than close the shared public archive.
  </p>

  <p>
    Administrative dashboards for campaign operations or site management may also remain private if they become part of
    hosted or managed services.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Scope of the Site</h2>

  <p>
    The primary focus of this site is <strong>world lore</strong> - information that defines Aletheia as a setting,
    independent of any single game or campaign.
  </p>

  <p>Over time, the site will also include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Public campaign notes from games set in Aletheia</li>
    <li>Protected or private campaign material where access is part of a real campaign space</li>
    <li>Shared reference surfaces such as maps, calendars, and timelines</li>
    <li>Observations, build notes, and lessons learned through play and maintenance</li>
    <li>Practical tips, tools, and links related to running and playing games in the setting</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Not all content represents the same level of abstraction. World lore is curated to remain internally consistent,
    while campaign material may reflect specific interpretations, timelines, or outcomes.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Game Systems</h2>

  <p>
    Aletheia is designed to be <strong>largely system-agnostic</strong>. The setting is intended to be adaptable to
    different tabletop role-playing systems.
  </p>

  <p>
    That said, some material - particularly campaign notes and practical advice - assumes the use of <strong>GURPS</strong>,
    which is the primary system used in our games. When system-specific assumptions are present, they are noted as such.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Who Is Behind Aletheia?</h2>

  <p>
    This project is maintained by two long-time tabletop role-playing gamers and fantasy world-builders. We have been
    playing and running RPGs on and off for decades, and Aletheia exists as a way to organize, refine, and share the
    world that the two of us have had in the back of our minds for many years.
  </p>

  <p>
    The site itself is self-built by Brad with AI assistance. It reflects an interest in durable publishing systems,
    maintainable content workflows, and keeping a long-running campaign archive readable over time.
  </p>

  <p>
    My brother also contributes to the setting and related campaign material. He is a fantasy world-builder and
    long-time gamer. Additional details about contributors will be added as the project develops.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Technical Notes</h2>

  <p>
    This site is an Astro-first build with an Obsidian-first content pipeline, cloud-backed collections, and
    authenticated campaign boundaries.
  </p>

  <p>
    It functions both as a public archive and as a reference implementation for the publishing and campaign tooling
    growing around it.
  </p>

  <p>
    The public project also serves as a reference implementation for an Astro/Cloudflare publishing model that may
    later support separate hosted or managed campaign services.
  </p>

  <p>
    Technical details and source:
    <a href="https://github.com/bradarnst/worldofaletheia">github.com/bradarnst/worldofaletheia</a>
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Current Direction</h2>

  <p>
    The current focus is to keep the public archive useful, open, and discoverable while learning whether optional
    campaign services could help other groups manage private campaign material.
  </p>

  <p>
    Support links, if present, are intended to help offset storage, compute, and maintenance rather than create paid
    access to the public archive.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Canon and Interpretation</h2>

  <p>Material published here represents the current canon of the world of Aletheia.</p>

  <p>
    Campaign notes and examples may depict specific events, perspectives, or outcomes that apply only to a particular
    game. Core world information is curated separately to preserve consistency across campaigns.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Contact and Transparency</h2>

  <p>
    This is a personal project, but thoughtful questions, corrections, and discussion are welcome - particularly
    regarding the setting, its assumptions, how the archive is built, or how the campaign platform ideas are taking
    shape.
  </p>

  <p>You can reach me at: brad [at] worldofaletheia.com</p>

  <div class="ui-surface ui-surface--muted not-prose my-8 p-6">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-ink-600">Support the project</p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-ink-700">
      World of Aletheia is maintained as an open project. If you want to help offset storage, compute, and maintenance
      costs as the archive grows, voluntary support is welcome.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-5 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="https://buymeacoffee.com/bradarnst" class="ui-button ui-button--primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Buy Me a Coffee</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/bradarnst/worldofaletheia" class="ui-button ui-button--secondary" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ui-surface ui-surface--muted not-prose my-8 p-6">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-ink-600">Ways to reach the project</p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-ink-700">
      Use <strong>Contact</strong> for a simple question or note. Use <strong>Contribute</strong> for corrections,
      archive feedback, typo reports, or collaboration ideas.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-5 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/contact" class="ui-button ui-button--primary">Contact</a>
      <a href="/contribute" class="ui-button ui-button--secondary">Contribute</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</SimpleContentLayout>
